      <description>Sir Alec Ogilvie was born in England, but went to India when he was three
            months old, where his father was assigned in the British Army's Foreign Political
            Department. Educated in England, Ogilvie retruned to India in 1935 where he joined a
            British company in Calcutta. He lived in Calcutta until 1965, except during World War
            II, when he served in the Indian Army from August 1940 to February 1946. Ogilvie was a
            Japanese prisoner of war. Though he began his career in the government, he spent most of
            his career in private business. This arrangement resulted from his father's prediction
            that British political authority would diminish over the next several decades. He lived
            in India a total of 36 years and reutned to England at the age of
            51.</description>
